Today, the Parliament of Ukraine in the course of amendments to the Criminal and Procedural Code rejected the attempt to cancel the article, according to which the opposition leader, Yulia Tymoshenko was condemned.
The amendment, which would lead to the release of the former prime minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the bill on the relief of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was recognised as unprofitable.
The judgment is not yet final; the court will consider the appeal of Timoshenko in December.
Timoshenko claims that the sentence is a political repentance of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of prejudice.
The proposal to abolish Article 365 of the Criminal Procedure Code, according to which the former Prime Minister was condemned, was supported by 147 members of the Parliament.
It would require 226 votes for its ratification.
