Dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state tourist agencies could work in former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was strictly restricted, tour agencies of that time were mainly selling tours to countries of the socialist block.
Thus, on holidays Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which caused significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist block (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips through socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter-invitation from that country was needed; otherwise individual travel was impossible.
At the time, tour agencies offered travel to the West, but it was necessary either to stand in a row all night, with a bed bag, or to have "good friends" in the agency.
And that was not all yet.
Currency permission was necessary for traveling to the West. It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely converted; without the exchange permit it was impossible to get cash (Western currency) for the trip to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the appearance of a large number of cottage and summer houses, this habit remains to this day.
After 1989, the tourism in the Czech Republic, thus, experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 vacation in Germany or Bulgaria was the culmination of our trips, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular now Croatia as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s the need for a visa to the neighboring countries of Western Europe was abolished. This set the start of a huge wave of short travel mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovak could not be saturated with traveling to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents as their revenue at the time was not enough for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of Czech tourism in that period was the desire to bring their own food (conserves, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely converted Czech crown. After decades, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our living level and average income increased, which around 1997 led to another important circumstance.
Since 1997, the increased demand has allowed tour agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines. Compared to the past, flights have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed world countries except the United States.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution took place in 2000. The large demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter flights from the Czech Republic will be shipped on twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, which symbolizes our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. canceled the need for a visa for Czech tourists. Our country, thus, forever joined the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15 thousand crowns per person during their holidays abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
