Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming a new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Breivik was a regular guy who exposed his anti-immigration views on the internet.
On Monday, Breivik, who was aware of the July mass murder in Norway that killed 77 people, appeared to his first open court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was far from alone on the net: he spent a lot of time preparing for an attack on his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After the summer tragedy, the researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
It’s easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
“We’ve understood that getting to them is not quite difficult,” says Jamie Bartlett, the leading author of the recently published European cyber-populism report at the British Research Center DEMOS.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says that researchers could easily use the advertising tool of the site to distinguish the required demographic group with scientific accuracy – what marketers have done for several years.
The Bartlett team found a half-million right-wing fans across Europe and then promoted advertising to them, but instead of showing a new group or a dietary product, the advertising offered the user to submit a survey in which there were questions about their level of education, attitude to violence and optimism regarding their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 participants in 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries – even without leaving the office.
“This is a completely new way of conducting research,” says Bartlett.
Some results are not so impressive: right-wing online parties are mostly young men, unhappy with immigration.
But suddenly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more reasonable, more democratic and less aggressive than those who are just hiding behind the monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and policy scientists use the site to study everything in the world - from health issues to social trends that are expressed in 'Like', wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three records a day, Facebook’s “super-actual information” is causing a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the title site by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it gives the opportunity to study people to whom it is impossible to reach on the street with a blocknote.
"Before, if you wanted to survey people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
“You would have to join the party, and they would never accept you,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you’re addressing them directly.”
Others say that with the help of this site it would be possible to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Meghan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues showed that students who discussed their drunk behaviors on Facebook were significantly more exposed to alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as their hostel tutors, could monitor the site and interfere to help a student who too often updates drunk status.
“You can’t solve the problem without discovering it,” said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
“We’ve found a way to identify children from the risk group that otherwise would not be detected.”
Facebook also constantly extract various types of data about its users.
The data processing group of the site processed the statistics of the status of relationships and Valentine's Day, the appearance of voters in the middle of the term in 2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (mainly using information that only they have access to - cyber freedom champions long insisted that the site should make its extensive collection of data publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend that is thousands of miles away from you, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a research they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined rules for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think many users at least thought about what a researcher can watch behind their profiles," says Neil Selvin, a sociologist from the London Knowledge Laboratory, about the study he conducted in 2006 using publicly available students' pages on Facebook.
“As much as they imagined, it was only between them and their friends.”
There is a question of methodology.
Even off-line has no guarantee that the subject of the study is extremely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to find out how much information in the user’s profile and page is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside Facebook are two completely different things,” Selvin says.
That’s why, despite his years of technological research, Selvin thinks that the blocknote and handbags are still the best research tools of those that can be used.
“Nothing can replace the way to the real world and the communication with real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about social, and the majority of social is still offline.”
