The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present a new government that will face the crisis that put Italy at the edge of an economic catastrophe and damaged the entire euro area.
A statement from the presidential palace said that Monty, appointed on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with President Georgi Napolitano to confirm that he could form a government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet consisting mainly of technocrates, although it is unclear when the new executive body will take its positions.
Monty said he would present the president the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to confirm my full confidence in our country’s ability to get out of this difficult period,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti didn’t say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles were overcome.
“The structure is now well drawn up,” he said.
Monty completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual as Italy faced the political and financial crisis that brought the size of their debt to a critical level.
The administration under the leadership of former European Commissioner Monty must approve the rigorous savings package required by European leaders to restore trust in Italy.
Based on the pressure on Monty to hurry, the unstable markets set the income from the BTP bonds of Italy for 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegalia, the leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after a meeting with Monty: "We said we will actively support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this critical situation.
Monty's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
“We believe that Professor Monty’s efforts must lead to a good outcome,” said Angelino Alfano, the secretary of the central-right party.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the government’s majority, consisting of the technocrates, which forms Monty.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty government must have strong parliamentary support for reforms that will likely be unpopular hard-saving reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts may lead to a new and destructive attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has increased pressure, warning that Monty’s failure could be a disaster.
Monty began consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women’s organizations on Monday.
He will finish the series of meetings on Tuesday evening.
Monty was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a short break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi will resign, the value of Italy’s debt has now reached a critical level in the background of uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
The rescue of Italy with a government debt of €1.8 billion would be too much for the modern financial defenders of the euro area.
Monty said his government would exist until the next 2013 elections, despite the widespread forecasts that politicians will only give him time to reform before appointing new elections.
Monty said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist that it should only be composed of technical experts, a proof of their dissatisfaction with the fact that the process is affected by the financial situation.
Political sources that mutual uncertainty and disagreement of the parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
