MSS announces obesity gen search program
Social protection leads the study on the search for the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by experts from the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which was named the Protocol "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence", which will provide a list of signs associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Department of medical research in the field of biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietologists and social workers was gathered.
This team is supported by specialists and graduates of the National Institute of National Health (NIPH) and the Center for Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (recommended or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where every Saturday, from 8:00 a.m., children will be tested.
He emphasized that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Kuala Lumpur (west of Mexico), and since October 8 the events are held at the sports center in Nassaualkoyotle (east of Mexico).
After the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children will be achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (South Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (North Mexico).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics for the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
The World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14th and the main objective is to gather 3,000 children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 with the permission of their parents and under their supervision to complete individual nutritional surveys.
They are also asked about physical activity and history of family hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He explained that on Saturday will be carried out anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, growth and range of the belt), blood pressure and levels of glucose, fats, cholesterol and insulin and genetic analysis (to identify the genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lopez said that this study reflects the concerns of health professionals about an alarming weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that in just 6 years there was an increase: in boys 77 percent suffered obesity, in girls 47 percent; in terms of overweight, there was also a significant increase,” said MSSI specialist.
He said that the reasonability of searching for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He that the average Mexican is 65 percent descendant of American Indians, 30 percent descendant of Europeans and 5 percent descendant of Africans and this condition affected the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that mainly the consequence of obesity genetics is the incapacity of the body to burn the excess of energy we consume (calories), and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for participants is a comprehensive assessment of children, which can determine whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark clusters on the neck (acts) and forearms means the probability of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is processed with all confidentiality, the doctors transmit it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that should be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruise Lopez explained that there are three main causes that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sitting lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of TV and using transport on small distances instead of walking.
This is also due to high calorie consumption, i.e. increased consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (thamals, bread, pizzas, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM can avoid fractures
Rafael Errera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, has developed a polymer-modified bitum to produce the best quality, environmental and temperature-resistant mixture.
If the signals sent by the road cover were paid attention, it would be necessary to repair about 200 thousand hams for every rain season in the capital area in the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Errera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM chemical faculty, and adds that if the process of building and keeping the asphalted road cover is correct, the number of hams can be reduced or completely reduced to zero.
In his lecture Technical Look at the Hole, read in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it is that the laboratory, for which it is responsible, develops a polymer-modified bitum to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitum, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitum can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of the roads and, therefore, to counter the formation of jams.
He explained that bitum, the heavest part of oil, is a sequence of carbohydrate molecules, some of which are high molecular mass called asphaltens, and others are low molecular mass called maltens, which together give the road cover its characteristic wise-thinking behavior.
The vibrant behavior of the bitum consists in the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a fluid, at 120 its vibration is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains almost a solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitum becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the street asphalt resistance is not constant, but changes over the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, a chemical engineering specialist said.
The scientist of Hymfak noted that the streets of Mexico are mainly covered with a flexible cover, which consists of six layers of material, of which the last three include bitum.
Among the top layers is a bitum composed of small stones left into bitum and then pressed.
Every stone that makes this cover, he said, is immersed in a bitum.
When driving vehicles and making efforts, this helps the forces to be very well distributed on the road cover.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt coating, he added, placed the last layer, which is called a layer of drainage, which is made of small stone, actually sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is the layer that will contact the wheels of transportation, it should have greater resistance than the asphalt cover and provide road treating.
As part of the road cover, which will receive and spread these efforts, the drain layer also requires the appropriate thickness, and it is necessary to take into account the material from which it is made.
Weather, especially moisture and temperature shifts, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the state of the asphalt.
When the earth is raw, the water penetrates into the cover and it is difficult to get out there, it causes the dilution of all layers of the cover and, therefore, the formation of hips.
During the formation of jams, he said, the first layer is drawn out and only then it affects the bitum, but the damage does not occur instantly, this is a process that should be paid attention at the first signs of the current repair programs.
Also, a member of the National System of Researchers explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of cover should always be linked to the transport load and it is necessary to ensure compliance with this requirement to prevent the frequent appearance of holes.
Rafael Errera said that relatively bitum much is still to be studied and done, for example, bitum emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help to make the caves with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
