Introduction to the Constitution of the "Golden Rule" of the Budget
The leadership of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats, which is in power in Austria, decided on Tuesday to record the budget "Golden Rule" in the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid the possible downturn by the rating agencies of the state credit rating of Austria (three-A).
Chancellor-social-democrat Werner Feiman personally announced this decision at the end of the Council of Ministers, with the Austrian government debt being 74.6%, which is significantly higher than the top threshold of 60%, established by the Maastricht Treaty, but below the government debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria’s payability fell by only one point, from the AA to the AA+, we would have to pay interests by three thousand million euros more each year, said Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister of Christian Democrats Michael Spindelegger.
Thus, Austria fulfills the requirement of the Eurozone summit on October 26 in Brussels; the heads of states and governments demanded a reduction of budget deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced government accounts through the constitution or equivalent law.
The resolution, adopted by the Austrian government, resembles the “German model” as Germany was the first European country to adopt the “Rule”.
By 2017, the structural deficit of the state budget should decrease by 0.75% of the gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017 the structural deficit of the state budget of the federal state in any year should not exceed 0.35% of the GDP, and land, like communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to make the government debt fall below the 60% mark established by the Maastricht Treaty, by 2020/2021.
