Energy Policy :
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be decided after a short discussion or under the influence of emotions, then it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing capacity and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings become a reason for consideration of the share and place occupied by nuclear energy.
The dispute will not bring fruit until all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options are studied.
France should build its opinion on objective facts and on rational data.
Now we are 7,000 million people on the planet, the demographic development will lead to double the need for electricity by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population will be deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to fill up the growing deficit of fossil resources to continue the production of electricity continuously, without forgetting the most important need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate imbalance – a topic that has disappeared from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
This is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case of Belgium, which puts its decision depending on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are determined to continue their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one installation to its set, renewing the construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident on the Tri-Mile Island.
Although the model of Germany based on renewable energy is sometimes given as an example, reality is contrary to this argument.
Berlin’s choice will result in increased cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, aggravated by increased demand for imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump of carbon dioxide emissions in connection with the construction of gas and coal stations.
Within a few months all these unpleasant effects will already be noticeable.
We should consider the example of Denmark.
The European champion in the construction of turbines, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to interruptive wind; resulting in carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices respectively 65% and 50% higher than the average in Europe.
On the other hand, thanks to the continuity of our energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalized economy the price per energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the service of industrial equipment on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear energy will lead to a great increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of the purchasing power.
The price that most French refuse to pay, especially because they do not object to this kind of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country’s energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 mediated.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole playoff of small and medium-sized enterprises specializing in international trade and creates a lot of jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France decided to give up nuclear energy, it would have to donate a large number of these enterprises and lose 6,000 million euros a year from French nuclear equipment and services exports.
Which electric engineer will order the EPR, planned to work for sixty years if it is planned to close its manufacturer?
To resolve the energy equation, it should be recognized that there are no divine or devil sources of energy production.
The development by Areva of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions, indicates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear energy,ining the highest level of security is undoubtedly vital.
In France, we have a security body that carries out uncompromised and transparent control of existing energy centers, such as Flamenville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is generally recognized, are full of the same assertion of safety.
Over the past 50 years, the nuclear industry has suffered three serious incidents.
Only one, Tri-Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any consequences for humans or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the installation of the reactor and unforgivable human error led to a tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two unprecedented natural disasters that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will get lessons from this accident, as it came from the two previous ones.
The fruit of this step and cooperation between security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, is a project that enables to counter such phenomena.
Since it is considered by all energy specialists who want to build a reactor, the stop of its construction in Flamenville will be a great gift to the competitors of Areva and EDF, cleansing them the way to conquer leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear energy.
It is necessary and legally to seek the best combination of energy for our country, but it would be irresponsibly to allow emotions, dogms and predicts to get the top of a dispute that is so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
