The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from various sides – the overload of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the digital policy and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a “state of human rights”.
Then there was the administrative disturbance of foreign students, which came into the news releases when the Minister of the Interior ("Liberation" from May 23) stated that France "no need foreign talents, stoneworkers and officers."
But it is very rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
Right and left are very agreeing on this.
In 1976, Jacques Chirac stated that “900,000 unemployed will not be a problem in the country with 2 million foreign workers,” and in 1990 Michel Rocker explained that France “can not accept the poor from all over the world.”
The difference is only at the level of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the country by the Polish water pipelines felt both left and right.
Both sides see immigration a burden for the French economy and for the French society.
The difference is only in the level of generosity they allow to show to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande was limited to banals, saying that “co-work will allow us to solve our immigration problem.”
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book that summarized the latest data on immigration (Special people: How migration formed our world and will determine our future, May 2011, Princeton University publishing, 352 p.), among experts there is a broad consensus on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that accept immigrants.
The limitation of immigration leads to weakening growth and decreasing employment.
The fears of the influence of immigrants are based on the idea that they are able to replace local workers, especially low-qualified, provoking a decrease in wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants supplement much more than they replace the local labor by performing jobs that lack the local labor.
Unqualified immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour, and the most qualified - in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as a surgeon would be difficult to work in a country where there is a lack of anesthesiologists, the mutual complementation existing between local and immigrants leads to the fact that the income of immigrants positively affects the wages of local workers.
Jovanni Perry estimated that an increase of 1% of the migration flow leads to an increase of 0.6-0.9% of real long-term wages.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity imported by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (a large proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prize winners, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo - all were based on immigrants).
Migrants also bring net profits to social security systems, giving an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labour Organization, for example, a immigrant arriving in Germany at the age of 30, for his life will bring to the state budget a net profit (income minus expenditure) in an average of €150,000.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of his term, was trying to "dental" to get into the missing growth points.
The mentioned teeth, which were used to scare immigrants, gave the exact opposite effect.
