The North Stream, a new gateway for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, is launched.
It is intended to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant manufacturer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of states and governments, took part on Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the orchestra's performance and exciting snacks, in the opening of the North Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mart Rutte together turned a symbolic valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Through the new gas pipeline 27.5 million additional cubic meters of gas will be delivered every year to Western Europe by the first pipeline of 1,224 km, which connects the Leningrad region with the territory of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready at the end of 2012, providing a total supply of 55 thousand million cubic meters of gas equivalent to all French consumption.
And the possibility of building the third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project encountered the strong resistance of Poland and the Baltic states.
The North Stream will actually allow the gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding the passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose part of their power: it will become more difficult for them to influence Russia, threatening to close access to the Western European markets.
At the most tensioned moment of the debates, Warsaw did not stop comparing the North Stream with the new German-Soviet Pact, indicating an alliance between Hitler and Stalin in order to occupy Poland in 1939.
This is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe seeks greater security of its supplies.
But the price of Europe’s energy deprivation, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to its understanding of a direct union between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, which consume large amounts of gas and whose own reserves are already on the outcome.
“This gas pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that connects us organically,” said François Fillon, opening the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent big gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the widespread smile on the faces of the Gazprom heads, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is a technical advance.
The submarine pipeline is made of steel locked into concrete to protect it from the boats of ships.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, we had to cross the mining fields left since World War II.
“The hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, the North Stream company’s spokesman.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal dragon with a weight equal to 242 Eiffel shells, without breaks throughout its length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers renounced it because Sweden was not excited that the Russian state company would forever settle on its shores.
“In the event of an accident, we will interrupt the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
Thus, in case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But it seems unlikely to the designers who designed shots designed to run only once every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the gas pipeline will be carried out by the submarine robot that pulls the ship for external observation, as well as by the apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigarette apparatus is inserted into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and thrown forward by the gas flow.
After arrival after 3 full days of journey at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any metal deformation.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for 50 years without the need for smallest repairs.
The circulation of the gas is only due to its pressure.
It is 200 bar at departure and 100 bar at arrival.
Five companies have joined their efforts to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint enterprise called the North Stream, which was commissioned to build and operate a gas pipeline.
His headquarters is located in Zuga, Switzerland, where taxation is favorable.
Then Gazprom leased the company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of the amount of gas it will actually be transported,” says Jens Müller.
The funding for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of the work will be 7.4 thousand euros for two pipelines.
The investment of GDF Suez will be about 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will pay their expenses because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline goes out of the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy shore planted with hollow trees.
The valves of 4.5 meters of height form a gas output terminal.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before transferring it to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full power it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Brands of Moleskine
Moleskine, created by the Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste to the letter.
He has the smell of adventures, the hours spent on the letter at the light of the candle.
The Moleskine block is easy to find on the straight-angle black coat, on the scratch, on the yellow-white sides, as if it wrapped with time.
However, the Moleskine recordbook, such as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, has decided to launch design blocks for sale.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company's consultant, took on the responsibility for the launch of a new product.
The block is inspired by the old manufacturing technique, the moleskin - a laked cotton tissue, which was used, for example, to cover the strawberries.
It is affirmed that this type of blocknotes are highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has matched today’s taste with the old and forgotten thing that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondy, who has since become the managing brand in Modo Modo.
Success has come.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We were far away from production in the first years, when only 3,000 blocknotes were produced.
Moleskine crossed the border of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It’s hard to set the profile of a typical buyer because the blockchain attracts a businessman, a student and a person of a free profession.
The buyers of Moleskine are cosmopolitan, have broad views and educated.
The small Italian company, which at first had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She spreads its blocknotes in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small cities and has been able to acquire widespread fame.
“We followed the spirit of time and this new need in the letter, despite the appearance of the email,” says Maria Sebregondi.
This characteristic cultural trait accompanies the development of Moleskine; recently the brand organized an exhibition "The Environmental Way", where architects and artists showed their own blocknotes.
In August, he also launched coverings with a leopard painting on the occasion of the film festival in Locarno.
Using its successes and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, handbags, computer bags.
Success that raised jealousy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was purchased by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which entered a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the rate of unemployment among disabled workers so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week of Disabled Employment begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled persons remains twice the average, namely 19% against 9% for the population as a whole.
is foolish?
“No,” says Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes the Week of Employment of Disabled People.
“In 15 years there will be significant progress.”
“At that time, the percentage of unemployed was not two, but three times higher.”
“There is still a lot of work ahead.”
There are many obstacles to employment for the disabled.
Among them more elderly: 37% over the age of 50 (17% in average).
They are more likely to have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree, and from 2.3 million students in higher education only 10,000 disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for disabled people against 38% in average.
In short, all these are criteria that make the return to work very difficult and that make the essence of the problem," said Christian Grapene, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies hire people with disabilities.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that changes, but too slowly.
A study conducted by the IMS-Entreprendre Association on Cité order in April showed that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “imaginated humans in wheels or mentally or mentally insufficient.”
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% of disabled workers, set in the law adopted in 1987.
The latest known figures for 2008 are 2.6%.
“Today we’re about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
The number of “taxed” organizations, as well as paid amounts, decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from 606 to 480 million euros) in 2007-2011.
“The 2005 law, which lifted the tax, created a strong pressure on the company,” explained Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects awareness growth, especially in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with a number of workers from 20 to 49 have disabled workers against 82% of organizations with a number of workers from 100 to 199.
